| **OWASP Top 10: 2021 → 2025** *Transition Reference Card  ·  What changed, what moved, what is new* Secure Web Application Development  ·  BBC Academy / JBI Training  ·  19–20 March 2026 |
| --- |

| **  Unchanged**  —  same position and name | **  Moved up**  —  higher risk ranking in 2025 | **  Moved down**  —  lower risk ranking in 2025 |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **  Renamed / reframed**  —  same position, broader scope | **  NEW in 2025**  —  no direct 2021 equivalent | **  Removed from Top 10**  —  absorbed into another category |

| **2021** | **OWASP Top 10:2021 Category** |  | **2025** | **OWASP Top 10:2025 Category** | **Change Summary ****&**** Course Notes** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **A01** | **Broken Access Control** | **→** | **A01** | **Broken Access Control** *→ No change* | Remains the most prevalent web application risk. Covers IDOR, missing function-level access control, forced browsing, and privilege escalation. All 2021 guidance still applies. **Course: **Module 6 |
| **A05** | **Security Misconfiguration** | **→** | **A02** | **Security Misconfiguration** *▲ Moved up 3* | Rises sharply in 2025, reflecting the explosion of cloud and containerised deployments where default credentials, exposed debug endpoints, and permissive CORS are endemic. Scope unchanged. **Course: **Module 7 |
| **A06** | **Vulnerable and Outdated Components** | **→** | **A03** | **Software Supply Chain Failures** *▲ Moved up 3 + Renamed* | Significantly broadened in 2025. Now encompasses dependency confusion attacks, compromised build pipelines, malicious packages (e.g. XZ Utils backdoor), and SBOMs. The old "outdated components" framing was too narrow. **Course: **Module 7 |
| **A02** | **Cryptographic Failures** | **→** | **A04** | **Cryptographic Failures** *▼ Moved down 2* | Scope unchanged: weak algorithms, hardcoded secrets, broken TLS, and sensitive data in transit/at rest. Slight fall in ranking reflects improved adoption of TLS 1.3 and secrets management tooling. **Course: **Module 8 |
| **A03** | **Injection  (incl. XSS)** | **→** | **A05** | **Injection  (incl. XSS + SSRF)** *▼ Moved down 2 + SSRF absorbed* | SQLi, Command Injection, XSS all remain. Crucially, SSRF (formerly A10:2021) is now treated as a type of injection rather than a standalone category. Content and exercises unchanged. **Course: **Module 9 |
| **A04** | **Insecure Design** | **→** | **A06** | **Insecure Design** *▼ Moved down 2* | Scope unchanged: absence of threat modelling, insecure architecture decisions, and missing security controls in design. Slight ranking drop does not diminish its importance in the SSDLC. **Course: **Module 10 |
| **A07** | **ID ****&**** Authentication Failures** | **→** | **A07** | **ID ****&**** Authentication Failures** *→ No change* | Unchanged in position and scope. Covers broken authentication, weak credential policies, missing MFA, session fixation, and credential stuffing. All ShopCo and Juice Shop exercises directly apply. **Course: **Module 6 |
| **A08** | **Software ****&**** Data Integrity Failures** | **→** | **A08** | **Software ****&**** Data Integrity Failures** *→ No change* | Unchanged. Covers insecure deserialization, unsigned CI/CD pipelines, auto-update mechanisms without integrity verification, and client-side data tampering. Juice Shop score/price manipulation exercises apply directly. **Course: **Module 8 |
| **A09** | **Security Logging ****&**** Monitoring Failures** | **→** | **A09** | **Logging ****&**** Alerting Failures** *→ Renamed (same position)* | "Alerting" replaces "Monitoring" in the name — a deliberate shift emphasising that logs are only valuable if they trigger timely alerts. The addition of "alerting" reflects SOC/SIEM integration expectations in 2025. **Course: **Module 11 |
| **—** | *(not in 2021)* | **→** | **A10** | **Mishandling of Exceptional Conditions** *★ New category  (SSRF → A05)* | SSRF exits as a standalone entry (absorbed into A05 Injection). The new A10 addresses improper error handling, stack trace disclosure, unhandled exceptions used as attack vectors, and fail-open security logic. **Course: **Module 10 |

| **The Two Genuinely New Things in OWASP Top 10:2025** 1.  A03 Software Supply Chain Failures replaces the narrower "Vulnerable and Outdated Components" framing. This is not just a rename — it adds an entirely new threat model: compromised build pipelines, malicious upstream packages, and SBOMs (Software Bill of Materials). The XZ Utils backdoor (2024) is the canonical real-world example. 2.  A10 Mishandling of Exceptional Conditions is a brand-new category with no 2021 equivalent. It covers improper error handling, information disclosure via stack traces, and fail-open logic where an exception bypasses security checks. |  | **What Happened to SSRF?** Server-Side Request Forgery (A10:2021) has been absorbed into A05 Injection in 2025. The reasoning: SSRF is fundamentally an injection vulnerability where untrusted data (a URL) is interpreted as a command (a server-side fetch). The defensive principle — never let user input directly specify what the server fetches — is identical to the injection principle of never letting user input become code. SSRF content is covered in Module 9 (Injection) in this course. The practical exercises using Juice Shop and the SSRF Anatomy reference card are unchanged. |
